                            href="https://github.com/SoorajModi/DataStructures">Data Structures</a> written in C.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="home-sub-header">
                <h2>Other things I've worked on...</h2>
                <p>
                    Beyond coding it is also important for me to me a member of my community and actively engaged with
                    opportunities around me. These have allowed to to develop essential skills outside of the technical
                    realm such as leadership, communication. problem solving, patience, initiative, and empathy.
                </p>
                <p>
                    These opportunities include being the President of the <a href="https://socis.ca">Society of
                        Computing and Information Sciences</a>, the Co-Chair of Student Senate Caucus, a Director for
                    the Central Student Association, the Director of Events for the Guelph Coding Community, a member of
                    Jack.org, and more. I loved all of these experiences in some way because they allowed me to have an
                    impact on the community, made the world a little bit better, and really gave me the chance to grow
                    as an individual beyond just a developer. They have been invaluable, and I taught me lessons I
                    will take with me into the future.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="home-sub-header">
                <h2>What I love about programming...</h2>
                <p>
                    Programming isn't just a profession for me. It's a passion, hobby, craft, and so much more. Although
                    there are times it gets frustrating, I find it incredibly rewarding. I consider myself a lifelong
                    learner and software development has more to learn than I could ever ask for. It feels whenever I
                    sit down and code, I pickup something new like a design pattern, tool, language, or something else.
                </p>
                <p>
                    I like to describe programming like playing with Lego. You gradually learn about the different
                    pieces, elements of an applications, and how they interact and work together. Eventually you can
                    put together a castle, car, an airplane, or anything you can imagine. Programming is similar, you
                    learn about the different pieces, the language, the framework, the different parts of a software
                    system like the frontend, backend, database, testing, and once you put it together, you can build
                    something amazing.
                </p>
            </div>
